<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Gummer not cowed by French trade warnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Agriculture minister John Gummer visits the Royal Smithfield Show, at
London's Earls Court yesterday.
Later Mr Gummer was told by Mr Jean-Pierre Soisson, his French counterpart,
that France would use the full force of the law to protect itself against UK
farm exports - particularly lamb, David Blackwell writes.
Mr Gummer, president of the EC Farm Council, said after lunch with Mr
Soisson that in his view France, as an important exporting country, needed a
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade settlement as much as any country in
Europe.
He added: 'France has 3m-plus unemployed. They will continue to be
unemployed unless we have a Gatt settlement.' He said that there was no
evidence for French fears that a Gatt settlement would not square with
reform of the EC's common agricultural policy.
Mr David Naish, president of the National Farmers Union, said the threats
made by some sections of French agriculture against British lorries was
outrageous. He added: 'We can understand the concern of French farmers and
others, but taking to the streets in a violent manner is not the best way to
make progress.'
</TEXT>
