<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Australian deficit worsens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Australian dollar fell below 68 US cents early today for the first time
in five years after the release yesterday of October balance of payments
figures showing a deterioration in the current account deficit, Kevin Brown
writes.
The government said the unadjusted deficit was just over ADollars 2bn
(Pounds 903m), compared to ADollars 1.7bn in September. The seasonally
adjusted deficit rose by 19 per cent to ADollars 1.8bn. The trend estimate,
which irons out swings in the seasonally adjusted figures, rose 5 per cent
to ADollars 1.5bn. This was the ninth successive monthly rise.
The main cause was an 11 per cent fall in exports, which was only partly
offset by a 4 per cent import fall. The underlying import trend was a record
high for the second month running. Economists said the continuing high
demand was surprising in relation to the slow recovery from the 1990-91
recession.
</TEXT>
