<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Big farm protest planned - Mitterrand
links French veto to final Gatt agreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH agriculture unions are expecting up to 50,000 farmers at a
multinational demonstration in Strasbourg today in protest at cuts in
subsidised exports of European farm produce proposed in the Gatt accord with
the US.
As farmers headed for Strasbourg, President Francois Mitterrand of France
said Paris would decide to accept or veto the farm trade agreement only
after a global world trade deal had been achieved. During a state dinner
with King Baudoin of Belgium last night, Mr Mitterrand said France would not
base a decision to reject a Gatt agreement on the agricultural issue alone.
The FNSEA, France's main farm group, said 8,000 German farmers would join
today's demonstration, in defiance of a warning to the DBV German farmers'
federation by Mr Ignaz Kiechle, German agriculture minister, not to support
France's threat to veto the deal.
There have been farm demonstrations against the farm trade deal in Belgium,
the Netherlands, Spain and Germany in recent weeks. But the French
government has attracted only moderate official support from its EC
partners, despite a diplomatic campaign to pull its allies into line.
Today's demonstration will provide a clearer measure of international
solidarity for French farmers, around 30,000 of whom are expected to be
there.
The presence of German farmers is unlikely to deflect Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's discreet attempts to encourage France, his main EC ally, to
compromise on Gatt. This is likely to be discussed at Friday's Franco-German
summit in Bonn. Before EC-US negotiators worked out their proposed farm
deal, the US had threatened to impose sanctions against some European farm
exports by next Saturday.
Delegations are expected from all EC member states and from farm unions
outside the Community, to make a general protest against the Gatt and US
trade policies. They include Canadians, Swiss, Scandinavians and a
delegation from a Japanese farm co-operative, angered at US rice growers'
efforts to gain access to their protected market.
Local authorities in Strasbourg have removed street signs to stop farmers
finding the European parliament and have ensured their route avoids the US
consulate and other US buildings.
</TEXT>
