<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / German union 'cautious' on pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES of a return to moderation in German pay deals were given a further
lift yesterday as the DAG union accepted that most of its 500,000 members
would receive no real increase next year, writes Christopher Parkes in
Frankfurt.
Mr Roland Issen, leader of the white-collar union representing public and
private sector staff, said claims for 1993 would range between 4.5 per cent
and 6.5 per cent. This 'cautious' starting point took into account fading
economic prospects and conditions in the industries employing DAG members.
The statement, together with last Friday's agreement among leaders of the
oTV to seek a basic 5 per cent increase for 2.3m public sector workers, will
dampen expectations among other wage earners and ultimately help reduce
inflation. The annual rate of price increases in western Germany, forecast
to average 3.5 per cent next year after 4 per cent this year, is a key
factor determining the Bundesbank's interest rates policy.
</TEXT>
