<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Twelve fail to agree on border controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC interior ministers yesterday failed to agree how to end internal border
controls on people before the end of 1993, let alone by January 1.
The London meeting was the last chance for ministers to agree a compromise
solution before the end of this year - deadline for the barrier-free single
European market.
Mr Martin Bangemann, EC internal market commissioner, proposed yesterday
that all member states should pledge to eliminate 'systematic' internal
border controls on people during 1993.
But Mr Kenneth Clarke, British home secretary, who chaired the meeting, said
afterwards that no member state could promise to lift all passport checks.
EC airports have already been given until December 1993 to lift controls on
internal EC flights. Britain is the firmest opponent of lifting internal
border controls on people and will go no further than reducing checks on EC
nationals to a minimum.
Mr Clarke, whose intransigence on the issue angered a number of ministers,
said member states were moving at different speeds towards the goal of
lifting controls. 'In my opinion there's no prospect of taking it very much
further forward until we see what the various member states do in the course
of 1993,' he said.
Continental member states intend to lift checks on all travellers within the
Community in due course, but are worried that external frontiers are not yet
strong enough.
However, Dutch diplomats said the UK presidency should have pressed for a
more positive outcome. Spanish officials also complained that their efforts
to lift controls by the end of the year would be undermined by delay.
</TEXT>
