<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Receivers called in as Rosehaugh loses battle with banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROSEHAUGH, a prominent property developer in the 1980s, yesterday gave up
its battle for survival. It owes its banks, led by Barclays, a total of
about Pounds 350m.
KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy firm, is expected to be appointed today
as its receiver, making Rosehaugh the latest high profile property company
to go into receivership this year. In contrast with a stock market value of
Pounds 746m in July 1987, Rosehaugh is now believed to have negative net
assets.
The downturn in the British property market, which has halved office values
in London over the past three years, is expected to result in several
billions of pounds of losses for banks operating in the UK.
Yesterday's move was the final stage in a lingering death. As the huge
losses accumulated over the past three years, it became increasingly clear
that Rosehaugh had no future. The company's former chairman and driving
force, Mr Godfrey Bradman, resigned from the board at the start of this
year.
Rosehaugh's best-known asset, the Broadgate office complex in the City of
London, is not directly affected by its receivership. It is owned by a
Rosehaugh subsidiary, Rosehaugh Stanhope Developments, which last week
secured its future through a refinancing of its Pounds 1.25bn debt.
That refinancing triggered the decision to put the rest of the company into
receivership. The reason for the receivership was partly attributed to the
banks' desire to cut Rosehaugh's overheads, particularly the cost of its
head office lease.
The decision by Rosehaugh's 26 banks to put the company into receivership
contrasts with their agreement, at the start of this year, to refinance
Rosehaugh's Pounds 310m of loans until January 1994. However, funds are not
committed in this type of banking standstill and so the agreement was not
binding.
In June 1991, Rosehaugh had net assets of Pounds 164m. In the year to June
30 1991, it reported losses of Pounds 227m, which followed losses of Pounds
166m the previous year.
Apart from Rosehaugh Stanhope Developments, Rosehaugh's principal asset is
Pelham Home, a landbank developer which partly owns the Chafford Hundred
housing scheme in Essex. It also owns commercial, retail and residential
properties.
Stanhope Properties, which jointly owns Rosehaugh Stanhope Development, with
Rosehaugh, said yesterday it was unaffected by Rosehaugh's receivership.
