<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Lamont faces payment probe: Spending watchdog to investigate
Pounds 4,700 government contribution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INVESTIGATION into a Pounds 4,700 government payment towards Mr Norman
Lamont's personal legal costs was launched by the National Audit Office last
night as the weekend disclosure of the contribution sparked a political row
at Westminster.
Sir John Bourn, the comptroller and auditor general, told the public
accounts committee of MPs he would conduct a close examination of the affair
for 'his own satisfaction and concern'.
Sir John heads the National Audit Office, the independent watchdog
responsible for monitoring government expenditure. He indicated that he
would report back to MPs in 'two or three weeks time' after studying the
relevant papers.
His decision came after the chancellor had sought to defuse the row -
arising out of his eviction last year of a self-styled 'sex therapist' who
had rented his London home - by publishing Treasury documents supporting his
decision to accept the money.
The documents showed that the payment had been made with the full approval
of senior civil servants. But they were dismissed as irrelevant by
opposition parties which demanded a House of Commons statement from the
chancellor.
Conservative MPs voiced fears that the controversy had further dented the
chancellor's reputation by putting a question mark against his political
judgment.
Ministers said there was no question of Mr Lamont being forced to resign. Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, dismissed the controversy as 'silly'.
But in private, senior Conservatives acknowledged Mr Major was under
pressure to move Mr Lamont from the Treasury in a new year cabinet
reshuffle.
Mr Lamont responded to the opposition attacks by publishing a minute
prepared by the then permanent secretary to the Treasury, Sir Peter
Middleton, setting out the case for a public contribution towards his legal
costs.
The document said it would have been 'unreasonable' for Mr Lamont to bear
all the legal expense because much of it was due to his position as
chancellor and the corresponding need to take immediate action.
It showed that Sir Peter had suggested that the Treasury might defray more
of the expenses than Mr Lamont accepted. The rest of the Pounds 23,000 legal
bill was met by anonymous Conservative benefactors.
In a letter to Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, Mr Lamont said the
documents fully supported his statements that the payment had been
legitimate. He also published extracts from the guidelines for Whitehall
civil servants which allow for ministers to be indemnified from public funds
in some legal actions.
Mr Brown said there was no precedent for a minister accepting taxpayers'
money to meet a private legal bill which was unrelated to his public duties.
Whitehall officials, however, were confident that Sir John's inquiry would
show that Mr Lamont and senior Treasury civil servants had acted entirely
properly.
Two lives of Lamont, Page 8
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
</TEXT>
