<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Cork Gully case disclosure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO PARTNERS from Cork Gully, the insolvency arm of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, gave
'inadequate' information to the court considering their application to be
appointed administrators to Polly Peck International, the
fruit-to-electronics group, their professional body said yesterday.
Mr Michael Jordan, head of Cork Gully, and Mr Richard Stone, head of
corporate finance, were both found guilty of misconduct on two grounds by
the professional conduct committee of the Institute of Chartered Accountants
in England and Wales.
They sought and accepted appointment as administrators while failing without
good reason to follow their professional ethics guidance, and when they
should have known there was, or appeared, to be a conflict of interest
between the firm, Polly Peck and Mr Asil Nadir, its chairman.
The charges came in the details of proceedings of the committee, made public
yesterday, a month after the two men were each fined Pounds 1,000 and asked
to pay Pounds 1,000 in costs.
The committee said the men offered no satisfactory explanation for the
inadequacy of information they provided to the court on October 25 1990. Had
they made proper inquiries, the fact they had a 'clear continuing
professional relationship' would have been clear, it said.
It also emerged that the statement issued yesterday was shown to Coopers
before it was released, and that alterations were made as a result.
Two footnotes to the judgment were removed - one which reproduced an extract
from the professional code of conduct, and another stating the maximum fine
which could be imposed at the time of the hearing was Pounds 1,000 per
person.
Mr Douglas Llambias, a council member of the Institute and its disciplinary
committee, said yesterday's statement should have been released at the time
of the original findings against the two men.
</TEXT>
