<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Yeltsin ban on party upheld: Court verdict makes symbolic
concessions to Communists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA'S highest court yesterday closed a drawn-out trial of the Communist
party with a compromise verdict that makes symbolic concessions to
supporters of the party without reversing its dismantling by President Boris
Yeltsin.
The decision by the Constitutional Court, which said Mr Yeltsin was right
after the August coup last year to ban the party's top bodies but not its
local cells, enables both sides to claim victory while sparing Mr Yeltsin
charges that he controls the courts. Such charges could have undermined his
authority at the Congress of People's Deputies which opens today amid
threats by deputies to press for the government's removal.
A political adviser to the government said a few ministers might be
sacrificed in the course of negotiations which will continue throughout the
Congress with the centrist Civic Union opposition group.
Mr Andrei Nechayev, the economics minister, even set out the possibility of
Mr Yegor Gaidar resigning as prime minister in favour of somebody who would
not interfere with economic policy. He also suggested a technical
resignation of the whole government which would, however, amount to little
more than a gimmick.
But Civic Union leaders are also divided over how far to push the
government.
The court, asked to review the legitimacy of President Yeltsin's decrees
disbanding the party and confiscating its property, found he was right to
dismantle its top bodies and take over state property appropriated by the
party. But it found against his decision to dismantle local branches and
against the transfer to the state of property paid for by rank and file
members.
Mr Valentin Kuptsov, one of the former senior Communists who challenged the
president's decrees in the court, said the decision gave the Congress 'good
grounds' to seek President Yeltsin's impeachment. It also cleared the way
for the Communist party to reconstitute itself and sue for the return of its
property.
However, it is difficult to see how party cells can reconstitute an
organisation with its top bodies still banned.
Lawyers for Mr Yeltsin suggested that property would not be retrievable in
the courts. The state would have to continue making it available to society
at large.
Russia and its western creditors remain divided over how much of the former
Soviet Union's foreign debt the country is capable of repaying next year,
putting off attempts to agree a debt rescheduling until mid-December. The
Paris Club of creditor states is offering a 10-year rescheduling with a
five-year grace period which would make Russia pay Dollars 5bn next year,
while Moscow is saying it can only pay Dollars 2.5bn.
The ball is still in the air, Page 16
</TEXT>
