<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Study finds fault with bank loan covenants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH BANKERS may have shown financial naivety when setting conditions for
loans with companies, an academic study suggests.
The current definitions in loan agreements between companies and banks of
ratios such as minimum net worth, interest cover or gearing are open to
widespread manipulation, the study found.
The conclusions come in an analysis of bank loan covenants by Mr David
Citron, a lecturer in accounting at City University Business School in
London.
Most banks attempt to safeguard their loans with performance linked to key
financial ratios, yet while the definitions are legally watertight most
leave enormous scope for creative accounting by managers determined not to
breach these ratios.
Bankers appear to have relied too much on their lawyers and not enough on
their accountants. In a survey of 29 leading lending institutions, Mr Citron
found that for loans over Pounds 1m more than two-thirds have financial
ratio covenants, rising to an even greater proportion for unsecured loans or
for those to companies with high gearing.
In a separate analysis of 25 bank loan contracts and 13 contract templates,
he found few of the ratios were directly linked to performance. The most
common were minimum net worth, interest cover and gearing.
On the definition of profit, he says: 'There is little evidence that
contracts attempt to adjust for accounting procedures that are particularly
susceptible to management discretion.'
Overall, he concludes: 'Some items are accepted as presented in the
accounts, thus leaving some scope for manoeuvre through a choice of
appropriate accounting methods.'
While some of the accounting ratios are more tightly defined with less scope
for abuse - such as assets - many measures are based on profits and so
remain open to manipulation.
Off-balance sheet finance is typically not considered, because most of the
ratios only specify the ratios in relation to the consolidated accounts of a
company.
The use of financial ratio covenants in UK bank loan contracts; Accounting
measurement rules in UK bank loan contracts. City University Business
School. Frobisher Crescent, Barbican Centre, London EC2Y 8HB
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
