<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Foreign Exchange and Money Markets: Focus on ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOBODY can say for certain that tensions in the European Exchange Rate
Mechanism are over, and there will be a strong focus this week on the
D-Mark's performance against the weaker ERM currencies, writes James Blitz.
The Irish authorities will continue to make a concerted effort to defend the
Irish punt this week, and overnight rates are due to be set at around 100
per cent from today.
There may be more intense pressure on the French franc. The French currency
fell through the FFr3.40 to the D-Mark level last week. Many analysts
continue to think that if there is strong pressure on the currency it will
come in the New Year, because dealers do not want to keep positions open for
long towards the year end.
The market remains undecided about whether the dollar can make a concerted
break through the DM1.61 level this year. Despite the uncertainties over the
ERM last week, the dollar failed to break through this level.
But according to strategists at IBJ International, there is a growing
perception that the currency will strengthen on further signs of economic
recovery.
Friday's non-farm payroll figure will give some further indication of the
scale of the economic upturn. However, the figure would have to be
particularly bad to prompt any easing in monetary policy from the Federal
Reserve.
Sterling was mostly sidelined last week, with strong support at DM2.42 and
resistance at DM2.44. With relatively little economic data due out this
week, the currency is likely to be confined to these ranges.
The sharp rise in Canadian prime lending rates in the last two weeks has
strengthened the Canadian dollar. There will be caution ahead of the
government's economic statement on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
