FT  30 NOV 92 / Chinese demands cast doubt on HK port project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA'S row with Britain about democracy in Hong Kong took a turn for the
worse at the weekend when senior Chinese representatives in the colony
attempted to cast doubt over the future development of Hong Kong's container
port.
Ma Yuzhen, China's ambassador to London, has been summoned to the Foreign
Office today to receive a toughly worded note from Mr Alastair Goodlad, a
foreign office minister, after Beijing demanded to be consulted on the
proposed development of the port's ninth terminal.
Officials in Hong Kong said the latest intervention by China was an attempt
to undermine confidence in the colony.
Beijing has claimed the proposed development of the port's ninth terminal
cannot proceed without China's agreement on terms under which government
land to accommodate the terminal will be sold to the terminal operators. The
government recently made a proposal to three operators, each of which has
substantial mainland Chinese links, over terms for proceeding with the
HKDollars 8bn to HKDollars 10bn (Pounds 854m) project.
The Hong Kong government denied the Chinese needed to be consulted over
terms of the sale of the land - permission for which was agreed with China
earlier this year. It pointed out that no government contracts or franchises
were being awarded.
China last year secured the right to be consulted on contracts and
franchises which span June 1997 - when Hong Kong reverts to Chinese
sovereignty - when it agreed to the construction of the new airport.
It has since refused to agree to financing arrangements for the airport
because it disagrees with Britain about the development of democracy in Hong
Kong.
The Chinese demand for consultation on the terminal was voiced by Guo
Fengmin, Beijing's chief representative to the Sino-British Joint Liaison
Group. It coincided with a vote by the colony's Legislative Council to
approve the administration's request for additional finance for the new
airport.
</TEXT>
