<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / KIO in Spain made large profits for outside accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE KUWAIT Investment Office, which claims to have lost billions of dollars
on industrial investments in Spain over the past few years, was at the same
time making large profits in Spain for institutional and private Kuwaiti
clients.
The profits were transferred to a number of hitherto unrevealed external
accounts the KIO was managing alongside the Kuwaiti oil revenue reserve it
traditionally handles.
A Financial Times investigation has uncovered evidence that the external
accounts were the main beneficiaries of the KIO's controversial investment
drive into Spain in the late 1980s. They may, in part, have made profits at
the expense of Kuwait's Reserve for Future Generations, which the KIO, one
of the world's most powerful and secretive investors, was created to manage.
Between 1986 and May this year the KIO spent Dollars 3.4bn (Pounds 2.2bn)
building one of Spain's largest industrial conglomerates. New managers who
took control of the organisation last spring have been investigating what
they claim are 'irregularities' in the handling of the Spanish assets bought
with the money.
The KIO holding company in Spain, Grupo Torras, now has debts of about
Dollars 3bn and a number of its affiliates have now either collapsed or are
close to failing.
The new KIO management claims that no profits were made in Spain and is
threatening to take legal action against the former leadership of the KIO
and its Spanish partners. But internal KIO documents show that by May 1990
the KIO's future generations account had made Dollars 24m in Spain while
some of its 'managed' accounts had made a profit of Dollars 231m.
A report produced last year by the KIO's auditor, KPMG Peat Marwick, details
transfers of profits made on share transactions from Spain to a series of
offshore companies - GSM Securities Management, Montrex and BPS - through
which the external accounts traded.
It has not been possible to identify the owners of the external accounts.
The KIO's constitution authorises it to manage any funds it is directed to
by the Kuwaiti government.
The KIO's relationship with the banking community in Spain and abroad is
already being tested by difficulties at Torras and some of its companies.
Last week Torras defaulted on loans worth a total of Dollars 400m from
Credit Suisse and Bank of America. The KIO itself had guaranteed these loans
and must repay them.
