FT  30 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As usual on Monday nights these days, the notable material all seems to be
factual. World In Action shows the first of a two-part report following
seven young people in the first year after they have been released from
institutional care (8.30 ITV).
In her series of Vintners' Tales Jancis Robinson tells of Arabella Woodrow
who is responsible for the wine sold by the Co-op. Working from a building
beside the Manchester Ship Canal, Dr Woodrow (PhD in biochemistry) orders
anything from packets of 100 cases to entire tankers containing enough to
fill 3,000 cases (8.30 BBC2). This year's Richard Dimbleby Lecture (10.10
BBC1) is given by Lord Taylor of Gosforth, the Lord Chief Justice, whose
subject is proposals for change in the judiciary.
If you intend to watch any of the programmes in connection with World Aids
Day tomorrow it may be as well to remember, given the desperate
determination of broadcasters to keep the true figures from the public, that
in Britain 94.9 per cent of Aids deaths occur in men and 5.1 per cent in
women. Aids Update 92 (10.40 ITV) is much concerned with women.
