<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Chief scorns critics of his Pounds 6m pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER WOOD, chief executive of Royal Bank of Scotland's Direct Line
Insurance subsidiary, yesterday pre-empted criticism of his Pounds 6m-plus
pay this year. 'The only people who will complain are ill-informed moaning
minnies,' he said.
Confirming that he was paid more than Pounds 6m in the year to September, Mr
Wood said he might earn a similar sum in each of the next two years.
Mr Wood, whose remuneration of Pounds 285,000 basic salary and a Pounds 6m
bonus payment is thought to make him the highest-paid British employee, said
he deserved the reward because of the rapid growth of the company, which he
had founded. He became a main board director of Royal Bank of Scotland this
summer.
The formula governing Mr Wood's bonus links his earnings to the rise in the
insurance subsidiary's value. He said that its rapid growth might give him
similar earnings for the next two years but they would fall after that.
Mr Wood said he would try to maintain his earnings by forming a company
called Direct Line Financial Services which would sell mortgages and
personal loans by telephone in the same manner as Direct Line Insurance.
'I started something from scratch, and I have satisfied my customers, my
staff and shareholders,' he said. The suggestion that it was wrong to earn
this amount was equivalent to 'saying that we ought to become like the
former Soviet Union'. He was talking openly about his earnings because he
regarded them as being fair.
If the net value of the company grows more than 12 per cent in a financial
year, Mr Wood will receive a bonus of one percentage point of the additional
increase in value. He earned Pounds 1.84m under the formula in the year to
September 1991.
Mr Wood founded Direct Line Insurance in 1985 and sold his 25 per cent stake
to Royal Bank of Scotland for a reduced price in 1988 in return for the
earnings formula. The subsidiary has 700,000 motor and 200,000 house
insurance policies.
He said the subsidiary was selling 50,000 motor and 8,000 house policies a
month. He would be 'very disappointed' if the company's net value was less
than Pounds 400m at year-end next September.
The bank is to announce its full-year results to September 30 this week. It
is thought to have disclosed Mr Wood's earnings earlier so that they did not
distract attention from the figures.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
