<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Companies look beyond perks ruling: How a decision in the
Lords will affect staff benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES are taking a fresh look at the perks they give their employees
following a landmark ruling in the House of Lords on Thursday.
Most companies will be relieved because the judgment - much to the Inland
Revenue's surprise - went in favour of the taxpayer. But much uncertainty
over the implications remains.
The case of Pepper vs Hart concerned 10 teachers from Malvern College who
argued that they should be assessed only for tax on any difference between
the reduced fees they paid for their own children to attend the school and
the marginal or extra cost of providing this education - to cover books,
laundry and food.
The Revenue argued that tax should be paid on any difference between the
fees and the average cost of providing the education. If the revenue had won
there would have been big implications for employee benefits.
The ruling has no effect on some perks which are dealt with under separate
rules and guidelines, including subsidised staff canteens and company cars.
But it has great significance for many, not least reduced-rate education for
teachers' children at other fee-paying schools.
Many London-based employers who offer subsidised or free sports facilities
will be affected. So will travel companies and tour operators offering
reduced-rate travel, lawyers providing conveyancing, manufacturers selling
products at a discount, restaurants offering meals to staff and companies
with executive dining rooms.
Mr Maurice Parry-Wingfield from accountants Touche Ross says it might also
have an impact on shareholders in some companies who receive benefits in
return for their investment as though they were employees.
A survey in October of more than 1,500 companies by accountants KPMG Peat
Marwick showed that 18 per cent of employers provided goods or services as a
benefit to their employees at less than average cost and that 16 per cent
provided sports and social facilities. Ten per cent of the companies said
they would withdraw some perks if Pepper vs Hart was decided in the
Revenue's favour.
British Airways offers staff concessionary travel for as little as 10 per
cent of the full fare. It was one of a number of companies and professional
firms to contribute to the fighting fund backing the Malvern teachers'
appeal.
Mr Clive Tulloch from Coopers &amp; Lybrand stressed that companies with
benefits in which the marginal cost exceeds the average cost will suffer as
a result of the judgement. That will include executives employing company
gardeners or chauffeurs at anti-social times such as weekends, when they
would be paid overtime above their normal rates.
The law lords' judgment for the first time allowed ministerial debate before
legislation to be considered alongside the letter of the law. That opens a
new line of legal attack for appeals in many types of case, and has big
implications for lawyers and accountants who will now have to consult
Hansard as well as the statute book.
But the ruling leaves many questions unanswered. The first question is
whether there is any recourse for companies which, under pressure from the
Inland Revenue, have used average cost as the benchmark.
Mr Brian Friedman, head of Stoy Benefit Consulting, said: 'Those companies
which have already settled are going to feel pretty sick.'
The second question is the continued uncertainty of how to calculate
marginal cost. BA - which recently reached a settlement with the Revenue on
its fares until April - is uncertain how to work out the costs of these
fares.
The third and most important question is how long the new procedures will be
in place. The Revenue appears to have been taken by surprise by the ruling.
Now it must clarify its position. It may well consider new legislation is
needed explicitly to require average costs to be used in future.
Next year there will be two budgets when the Revenue could propose this. It
has promised a statement shortly.
No Revenue press release is likely to be scrutinised more closely.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4927</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK3BQABAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / New fears raised over coal jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY ABOUT a third of the 31 threatened British Coal pits would be saved
even if the most radical measures to boost demand for UK coal were adopted,
one of its senior executives said last night.
Mr Andrew Horsler, director general of marketing, said the most radical
measures could provide a market of 50m tonnes. That compares with 40m tonnes
which British Coal has tentatively agreed to sell the electricity generators
next year and 30m in the following four years.
On the BBC2 Money Programme, Mr Horsler said that if 50m tonnes could be
achieved it would result in 10 to 12 of the 31 threatened pits being saved.
His estimates underline the difficulties the government will have in
formulating an energy policy which saves enough coal jobs to satisfy MPs and
the public.
Separately, further opposition has emerged among the regional electricity
companies to suggestions that the government should delay a planned increase
in competition in the industry to make room for a bigger coal market.
Seeboard, serving Kent, Surrey and the Sussex area, has told MPs inquiring
into energy policy that deferring liberalisation would strengthen the
position of the two main electricity generators and frustrate customer
expectations of increased choice of supplier.
Last week suggestions by Southern Electric to the Commons energy committee
that liberalisation could be postponed to allow electricity companies to buy
an extra 15m tonnes of coal a year on medium-term contracts were criticised
by Eastern Electricity. It had been assumed that most other regional
electricity companies would accept such a solution, in part because of fears
about the effects of increased competition.
Under the plans the competitive part of the market, which is restricted to
large companies, would be open to medium-sized companies in 1994. In 1998
all customers, including households, would be able to choose from which
company to buy electricity supplies.
Prof Stephen Littlechild, the industry regulator, strongly supports
increased competition and some believe his position would be untenable if
liberalisation plans were modified significantly.
For this reason some regional electricity companies would be happier with a
compromise.
East Midlands Electricity has applied to the Department of Trade and
Industry for a licence to supply regional customers with a range of
telecommunications services.
</TEXT>
