<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Tarnished Lamont starts to lose support: Talk among Tories
about a successor is spreading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN POLITICS, image counts for as much as substance. So the political damage
inflicted on Mr Norman Lamont by the disclosure that the Treasury helped to
pay one of his personal legal bills has little to do with the merits of the
argument.
As the weekend reports about the chancellor's financial affairs dealt
another public relations blow to the government, the view among senior
Conservatives was that Mr Lamont's image had been badly tarnished.
The hardening consensus was that Mr John Major should move him from the
Treasury in a new-year cabinet reshuffle. Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary,
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mr Michael Howard, environment
secretary, were being cited as front-runners for his job.
No one was suggesting that Mr Lamont had broken the rules by accepting the
Pounds 4,000 payment towards a Pounds 23,000 bill incurred after he
discovered 18 months ago that the tenant in his Notting Hill house was a
self-styled sex therapist.
The contribution had been approved by Treasury officials who had judged that
it matched the expenses he had incurred directly as a result of his public
office. The taxpayers' contribution covered the initial handling of press
inquiries, not the subsequent legal bill to evict the tenant.
According to senior Whitehall insiders Mr Lamont had not asked for the
money. Instead it had been offered after his officials judged that
protecting the reputation of the chancellor was a legitimate public expense.
The payment had been approved both by Sir Peter Middleton, then permanent
secretary, and by Sir Terence Burns, his successor. An explanation of the
expenditure had been sent to the National Audit Office.
Whatever the proprieties, ministerial colleagues acknowledged yesterday that
Mr Lamont had made a serious political misjudgment. They queried also
whether he should have accepted the generosity of the anonymous Conservative
benefactors who paid the remainder of the legal costs.
The timing could not have been worse. A few days earlier the disclosures
about Mr Lamont's credit-card record had indicated that the chancellor had
been repeatedly behind in meeting his repayments. Taken together the two
events conveyed an image of a chancellor living beyond his means, a bon
viveur charged with stewardship of the nation's finances but careless about
his own.
As one minister put it last night: 'Accepting taxpayers' money does not say
much for his judgment.'
In more tranquil times Mr Lamont might have been able to brush off the
controversy. But two years of deepening economic gloom and the
disintegration on September 16 of the government's economic strategy with
sterling's withdrawal from the ERM have seriously undermined his reputation.
Neither the Conservative party nor the electorate are in a forgiving mood.
Mr Lamont's position had been underpinned by his support on the right of the
party. A Euro-sceptic, he has made clear that he is in no hurry to take
sterling back into the ERM. But this weekend his admirers were beginning to
question whether, with Mr Lamont at the Treasury, the government could hope
to re-ignite the consumer and industrial confidence central to its hopes of
economic recovery.
There are signs of strain between Mr Major and Mr Lamont. The prime
minister's friends have made clear that the economic recovery package in
this month's Autumn Statement was a source of friction between the two men.
The chancellor is said to have sought to trim Mr Major's ambitions.
Mr Lamont has told his allies that he has an assurance from the prime
minister that his position is secure, but the relationship between the two -
the most important in the government - is businesslike rather than friendly.
Nor is Mr Lamont's reputation high within the Treasury. He is judged to lack
the intellectual clout - and capacity for hard work - of some of his
predecessors.
Some senior Conservatives were saying last night that Mr Major might yet
seek to avoid until the summer a reshuffle that would anger Tory
Euro-sceptics. The government is already faced with the prospect of a series
of backbench revolts against the Maastricht bill. To move Mr Clarke or Mr
MacGregor - both prominent pro-Europeans - to the Treasury could increase
the number of potential rebels. Mr Howard, the most junior candidate, alone
among the front-runners shares Mr Lamont's instincts on Europe and the ERM.
Mr Clarke, widely acknowledged to be the most powerful minister in Mr
Major's cabinet, has by far the strongest claim to the chancellorship. Mr
Lamont could be moved to the Home Office or, in a wider reshuffle, to
defence.
Mr Major is a cautious politician but he may have to take the risk. After
the traumas of the past few months he and his government need above all to
demonstrate that they have re-established a grip.
Putting Mr Clarke in 11 Downing Street could do it.
</TEXT>
