<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Smith to seek overhaul of 'creaking constitution'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, opposition leader, is to urge a new relationship between
government and citizens as part of a Labour policy on what he calls
Britain's 'creaking constitution'.
In a speech to be made either before Christmas or in the new year he will
address what he sees as growing public disenchantment with the 'elective
dictatorship' and with what is seen as arrogance from ministers in their
exercise of power.
Mr Smith believes the handling of the pit closures was just one recent
example among many of disquiet among voters at the lack of consultation
between governors and governed. Another was the so-called Iraqgate
disclosures over the sales of machinery with military end-uses to Iraq.
Labour is already committed to a freedom of information act, a bill of
rights and reform of the House of Lords. Mr Smith is expected to add new
proposals on increasing the accountability of politicians to the public and
parliament.
These could include new powers for Commons committees to inquire into the
actions of government departments and measures to apply the European
Community's subsidiarity principle to the devolution of powers from
Whitehall to the regions. The Maastricht treaty was 'the best deal on
offer', Mr Jack Cunningham, the shadow foreign secretary, said yesterday.
But he refused to pledge Labour's support for the third reading of the Bill
to ratify the treaty.
Leftwing Labour MPs are showing unease at the party leadership's European
policy. They argue in a paper published by the 100-strong Tribune group that
Labour should support a federal Europe and take a much more active role in
pushing for a more democratically accountable EC.
</TEXT>
