<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Warning of 3.25m jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of people unemployed and claiming benefit will continue to rise
until at least the spring of 1994, the independent Employment Institute has
warned.
By then, it says, almost 3.25m people will be unemployed compared with the
current 2.8m.
The institute, a research and consultancy body, analyses the chancellor's
Autumn Statement in a report and says a clear flaw in the package was the
failure to do more to help the unemployed, particularly those out of work
for more than 12 months.
It adds that the government's decision to offer more opportunities on job
search programmes was welcome but not enough. It questions the funding of
programmes for the adult unemployed - Employment Training, the main training
scheme, and Employment Action, the work experience scheme, have been
combined. The new scheme, to be called Training for Work, will have a budget
of Pounds 936m in 1993-94 - Pounds 40m less than is being spent on ET and EA
this year.
Training places should have been expanded. 'This is the ideal time to
re-skill the unemployed and help reduce the skill bottlenecks which fuel
inflation and which will inevitably occur when the economy begins to grow
more rapidly.'
The institute says skill bottlenecks will be only one of the supply-side
problems.
It points out that although unemployment is rising the Department of
Employment's budget will be a third lower in real terms in 1993 than in
1987-88, when unemployment was falling.
Economic Report Volume 7. Employment Institute, Southbank House, Black
Prince Road, London SE1 7SJ. Pounds 3.
</TEXT>
