<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / InterCity's passenger's Charter fails to meet required
levels
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL'S InterCity sector is set to end the first year of the
Passenger's Charter with all seven of its 'routes' (groups of lines) failing
to meet the required levels of punctuality, reliability or both.
Three of its routes - Anglia, West Coast and Cross Country - are falling so
far short of their punctuality targets that they look likely to trigger 5
per cent discounts for passengers renewing season tickets.
Two more routes - Midland Main Line and Gatwick Express - are performing so
poorly on reliability that these, too, look likely to trigger 5 per cent
discounts.
The Great Western and East Coast routes are also failing to meet one or both
targets. In neither case, however, does the margin reach the level necessary
to trigger discounts.
InterCity says the targets it has been set are unrealistic because they
require all routes to perform to the standards of punctuality and
reliability regardless of whether they have been modernised. It wants
separate targets for each route. The government has rejected the idea
because the result would be a softening of targets for most lines, and
ministers are not prepared to concede a relaxation of the Passenger's
Charter.
