<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / BR compensation likely to be limited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMUTERS on British Rail's Network SouthEast services are likely to find
that only one - if any - of the network's 15 routes will have performed
badly enough by the end of the year to trigger compensation under the
Passenger's Charter in the form of discounts for season tickets.
The results are likely to bring criticisms that the performance targets,
which vary from one Network SouthEast route to another according to the
investment they have received, are too easy.
The only route likely to make a pay-out this year is the Kent Coast line
which is failing to get the required 82 per cent of peak-hour trains to
their destination within five minutes of the scheduled time. So far this
year it has managed only 78.5 per cent.
Network SouthEast said reasons for the route's poor performance included
preparations for the Channel tunnel as well as train failures and leaves on
the line.
If its performance fails to improve, commuters using the route will get a 5
per cent discount on the renewal price of their season tickets. But if the
line can bring punctuality to within 3 percentage points of the target in
the last few weeks of the year, it will still avoid having to pay
compensation.
Network SouthEast said the purpose of the targets was to improve the
performance of the railway, not to hand out cash. The fact that
season-ticket discounts were unlikely to be triggered indicated that the
targets were achieving their objective.
The government points to the performance of lines such as the rundown route
between London and Tilbury and Southend in Essex, which, although it has a
punctuality target of only 80 per cent, is actually achieving 90.3 per cent.
Ministers say this supports the belief that performance is as much a matter
of organisation and management as of investment. They are therefore likely
to set much tougher targets for all lines next year including the
under-invested ones. Five of the 24 Regional Railways routes will give
discounts to season ticket holders if their performance does not improve by
the end of the year. They are Cross Country; East Midlands and Lincs; West
Midlands; Cardiff Valleys; and North East services.
</TEXT>
