<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / Major warns of market risks if EC summit fails: PM will tell
counterparts to compromise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR will this week warn of the danger of fresh turmoil in
international financial markets if the European Community fails to resolve
its differences in a comprehensive accord at next week's Edinburgh summit.
As he embarks on a new round of diplomacy today, the prime minister is
preparing to tell fellow heads of government that a series of complex deals
must be reached to restore market confidence, fuel recovery and thereby
prevent the recession deepening into a slump.
With mistrust of the British presidency of the EC still running high in
European capitals, Mr Major must persuade his counterparts to compromise on
issues ranging from the Community budget to enlargement and the political
crisis caused by Denmark's rejection of the Maastricht treaty.
In Brussels, senior EC officials are concerned that Mr Major may be gambling
too much on his powers of personal diplomacy to forge the alliances
necessary to avoid failure at Edinburgh.
The prime minister's task has become trickier as France has stepped up its
campaign to peel away support for the EC-US compromise on farm subsidies in
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks.
A solid EC majority remains opposed to scuppering the deal, but some
countries such as Spain and Belgium appear to be wavering. Mr Major is in
Luxembourg today and will hold crucial talks in Madrid tomorrow with Mr
Felipe Gonzalez, the Spanish prime minister. His support is needed to meet
Danish requests for exemptions from the Maastricht treaty and to overcome
Madrid's opposition to opening talks early next year on EC enlargement with
Austria, Finland, Sweden and Switzerland.
But Mr Gonzalez is bitterly disappointed at the UK's tough new proposals on
the shape and size of the EC budget leading to the end of the decade. The UK
plan was presented to a meeting of EC foreign and finance ministers in
Brussels last Friday, and drew a storm of protest from poorer EC countries
led by Spain.
A British minister said last night, however, that it was becoming
increasingly clear that agreement on the future financing of the community
would hold the key to the summit. Although almost every country is seeking
agreements on a wide range of issues, an accord on the new shape of the
Community's financing would 'unlock everything', he said.
Britain wants to freeze EC spending for the next three years, and to limit
growth to a 'ceiling' of 1.22 per cent of the Community's gross national
product in 1996 and 1997, before lifting it to 1.25 per cent in 1998 and
1999. The approach won support from Germany, the Netherlands and richer EC
members, but Greece, Ireland, Spain and Portugal denounced the compromise
and called for the allocation of greater resources known as 'cohesion
funds'.
France has been wooing Spain in an effort to build a coalition in favour of
renegotiating the deal with the US on farm subsidies on the grounds that it
is not compatible with the EC agreement last May to reform the Common
Agricultural Policy. The aim is to end France's isolation within the EC on
the Gatt trade talks, thus avoiding the exercise of a French veto which
would provoke a serious split in the Community.
Speaking on French television yesterday, Mr Dominique Strauss-Kahn, France's
industry and trade minister, described a French veto as akin to using a
nuclear weapon. At the same time, he brushed aside fears that reopening the
farm subsidies deal could jeopardise hopes of a wider Gatt agreement.
