<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 92 / International Company News: German subsidiary drags Kewill
into midway loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH COSTS and poor sales at one German subsidiary forced Kewill Systems
into a small loss midway and cast a pall over prospects for the full year.
The Surrey-based computing services company, which markets a portfolio of
manufacturing and accounting software products, incurred a pre-tax loss of
Pounds 172,000 for the half year ended September 30, compared to a profit of
Pounds 1.7m.
Turnover fell from Pounds 21.46m to Pounds 15.42m, reflecting the continued
shrinking of Weigang, one of the German companies, and a movement away from
hardware distribution in Europe.
Losses per per share amounted to 3.58p (earnings 13.56p).
Mr John Overstall, chairman, said once the Weigang situation had been
resolved the company would apply to the Court to approve a capital reduction
to eliminate the deficit on distributable reserves.
He said most of the operations had continued steadily. Triffid Software, in
particular, had contributed Pounds 600,000 of UK operation's total pre-tax
profits of Pounds 1m. Han Dataport, the other German subsidiary, made Pounds
500,000.
Weigang lost Pounds 1.3m, however, after a sharp fall in orders at the end
of 1991. Interest costs rose to Pounds 413,000 (Pounds 279,000).
Mr Overstall said marketing efforts had been stepped up in Germany and staff
at Weigang should be reduced to 29 people by April next year. The company
still retained some 400 German customers and should break even next year.
