<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 92 / International Company News: NEC says charges will push it to
Y9bn loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEC, the Japanese electronics company that dominates the domestic personal
computer market, yesterday said it would post a consolidated net loss of
Y9bn (Dollars 72.58m) in the 12 months to the end of March next year. The
company earned Y15.28bn last year.
NEC has been hit hard by the decline in domestic capital spending and the
sluggishness of personal consumption, which have eaten deeply into sales in
its main lines of business. In the half-year to September, net profits
declined by 77.3 per cent to Y4.25bn. Sales fell by 7.1 per cent to
Y1,688.2bn.
However, the company expects second-half results to be much worse because of
two factors: rising depreciation charges stemming from the completion of
semiconductor manufacturing facilities in North America and Japan, and
charges resulting from a restructuring of NEC's home electronics business in
North America.
On a pre-tax level, profits in the first half of the year plunged by 83.9
per cent to Y8.26bn. For the full year, the company expected Y10bn in
pre-tax profits.
For the interim period, sales of communication systems and equipment were
down 9 per cent to Y452.98bn. Computers and industrial electronics systems
were down 6.3 per cent to Y838.7bn, while electron devices, including
semiconductors, fell 6.9 per cent to Y299.2bn.
</TEXT>
