</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SURREY Group, the bookmakers, reported a Pounds 946,000 pre-tax loss for
the half year to September 30 compared with profits last time of Pounds
117,000.
At the same time the group announced the disposal of 26 betting shops in
Scotland to Stanley Racing, a subsidiary of Stanley Leisure Organisation,
for a maximum Pounds 2.99m in cash.
Mr R Green, the chairman, said the proceeds would be mainly used to reduce
borrowings. Interest payable for the six months totalled Pounds 368,000
(Pounds 272,000).
As a result of the disposals, which follow the sale of the majority of the
group's betting shops in East Anglia, Surrey has been able to renegotiate
its bank facilities with its principal banker, Allied Irish Banks. The
directors consider the new working capital to be sufficient for the group's
current requirements.
Mr Green said that in the half year margins had been lower than for some
years. Since the period-end there had been some improvement but it was too
early to tell whether that was likely to continue.
Turnover improved to Pounds 27.9m (Pounds 26.1m) but cost of sales increased
to Pounds 25.2m (Pounds 23m) and there were higher administrative costs of
Pounds 3.26m (Pounds 2.73m).
Losses per share amounted to 0.49p (0.09p earnings).
An extraordinary meeting to consider the disposal proposals will take place
on December 16.
